It’s interesting how subtle regex can be! The pattern `^\s*` can match one or more newline characters right at the start of a line. For example, in the text "abc\n\n====", the match actually starts at index 4, which is the empty line. The `\s*` captures the newline before the equals signs, meaning that the delimiter index would include that blank line. It's a neat aspect of regex I've got to keep in mind!"}]}
